Edit S:\01_Repos\BeFirst_Portal\firstronic\Areas\Manage\Views\Station\_CreateOrUpdate.cshtml

Find the Building_Key dropdown field (currently around line 152-159):
```cshtml
<div class="uk-width-1-3@s">
  @{
    var builinglist = Firstronic.Framework.Functions.Queries.GetSelectedFromQuery("SELECT [Building_Key] ,Name FROM [PLEX_Common_v_Building] order by Building_Key");
  }
  @Html.LabelFor(y => y.Building_Key, new { @class = "m-0 fs-14" })
  @Html.DropDownListFor(y => y.Building_Key, (IEnumerable<SelectListItem>)builinglist, new { @class = "md-input", @id = "ddlBuild" })
</div>
```

And the AreaID dropdown field (should be just before Building_Key):
```cshtml
<div class="uk-width-1-3@s">
  @Html.LabelFor(y => y.AreaID, new { @class = "m-0 fs-14" })
  @Html.DropDownListFor(y => y.AreaID, (IEnumerable<SelectListItem>)areasavailables, new { @class = "md-input", @id = "ddlArea" })
</div>
```

**Swap their positions** so Building_Key comes before AreaID. This will move Building to Row 2, Column 3 and AreaID to Row 3, Column 1, creating better visual balance.

IMPORTANT: Keep the @id attributes intact (ddlBuild and ddlArea) as they're used in JavaScript.
